body:
**Description**
While the Cartesian product feature of nesting GENERATE calls is useful in some contexts, the use case I have is more pedestrian.

I'd like to use a generator to generate a number of random values per test case.  I ended up writing something that creates a std::vector, where I extract each element individually for the test case.

NOTE: I'm aware the random generator is not a good implementation. Just used here for illustrative purposes.

```
template<typename Container, size_t NUM_ELEMENTS=1>
class RandomValuesGenerator : public Catch::Generators::IGenerator<Container>
{
public:
	using value_type = typename Container::value_type;
	RandomValuesGenerator()
	{
		_current_value.resize(NUM_ELEMENTS);
		static_cast<void>(next());
	}
	
	Container const& get( ) const override
	{
		return _current_value;
	}
	
	bool next() override
	{
		for (size_t i = 0; i < NUM_ELEMENTS; i++)
		{
			_current_value[i] = value_type ( 1e3 * (drand48() - 0.5) );
		}
		return true;
	}
	
private:
	Container _current_value;
};

// Convenience function for creating a Catch2 generator for producing random numbers
template<typename Container, size_t NUM_ELEMENTS=1>
static Catch::Generators::GeneratorWrapper<Container> randomValues() {
	return Catch::Generators::GeneratorWrapper<Container>(
		std::unique_ptr<Catch::Generators::IGenerator<Container> >(
            new RandomValuesGenerator<Container, NUM_ELEMENTS>()));
}
```

Where I call the code like so:
```
TEST_CASE("someTest") {
    const int numTrials = 10;
    auto values = GENERATE(take(numTrials, randomValues<std::vector<float>, 4>()));
    float a = values[0]; CAPTURE(a);
    float b = values[1]; CAPTURE(b);
    float c = values[2]; CAPTURE(c);
    float d = values[3]; CAPTURE(d);

    SECTION("Section1") {
        SECTION("SubSection 1.1") { ... }
        SECTION("SubSection 1.2") { ... }
    }
}
```

Where it will generate n-tuples of random numbers to be used in the various subsection tests below.
I imagine there should be a better/easier way to do this as I really just want to set up the number of trials I want to do, and have any number of local variables pull digits from the generator.  E.g. I feel like I shouldn't have to tell it to use a std::vector just to extract values from it into separate variables.

E.g. something like
```
TEST_CASE("Ideal") {
    int numTrials = 100;
    int numVars = 4;
    auto generator = GENERATE(take(numTrials*numVars, randomFloats());
    float a = generator.get();
    float b = generator.get();
    ...
```

Is there a way to do this?
